star lot
Homonym Number:
Word Class:noun
Sense Number: 1
Definition:[wool sales] a sale of three bales or less in one offering [often made up of locks, pieces or matted fleeces.]
Origin:[none]
Register:
Register 2:
Flag: Farm Words
Domain:Rural
Region:[none]
See:
Pronunciation:
Notes:
Citations
Date: 0/0/1982
Source: MAF Agricultural Glossary
Author:
Vol / Page: 59
Edition:
Quote: <i>Star lot</i>: Lot of wool of less than four bales, or three in the case of super wool. Generally sold after the main catalogue.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1897
Source: Practical Treatise on Wool and Sheep Breeding
Author: BISLEY
Vol / Page: 43
Edition:
Quote: .. we deem it advisable, in this connection, to draw special attention to the selling regulations with regard to star lots (that is parcels of three bales and under.) Star lots are sold subsequently to the lots of four bales and over.
Notes:

Date: 19/9/1903
Source: Farmers' Union Advocate
Author:
Vol / Page: 4
Edition:
Quote: He objected to have a pound of wool taken off every parcel; to have 12 lbs deducted per bale if it weighed only 10lbs, to the system of 'star' lots, under which the small farmer loses the competition of foreign buyers.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1919
Source: Wool in NZ
Author:
Vol / Page: 31
Edition:
Quote: .. he [the small farmer] also loses through having it [wool] sold in very small lines, known as 'star lots.'
